<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-elementary-matrices">
  <title>Module 2: Elementary Matrices</title>

  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <title>Topics and Objectives</title>
      <p>We will explore the following concepts in this section:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>the inverse of a matrix, its algebraic properties, and its relation to solving systems of linear equations</p></li>
        <li><p>elementary matrices and their role in calculating the matrix inverse</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Objectives: After this section, students should be able to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>apply the formal definition of an inverse and its algebraic properties to solve and analyze linear systems</p></li>
        <li><p>construct elementary matrices and characterize row operations with them</p></li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-inverse-properties">
    <title>Properties of the Matrix Inverse</title>
    <p>
      Assume <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are invertible <m>n \times n</m> matrices. The following properties hold:
      <ul>
        <li><p><m>(A^{-1})^{-1} = A</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>(AB)^{-1} = B^{-1}A^{-1}</m> (Note: matrix multiplication is non-commutative!)</p></li>
        <li><p><m>(A^T)^{-1} = (A^{-1})^T</m></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <title>True or False</title>
      <statement>
        <p>True or false: <m>(ABC)^{-1} = C^{-1}B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>True. The inverse of a product of any number of invertible matrices is the product of their inverses in the reverse order.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-defining-elementary">
    <title>Elementary Matrices</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-elementary-matrix">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>elementary matrix</term>, <m>E</m>, is one that differs from <m>I_n</m> by exactly one row operation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Recall our elementary row operations:
          <ul>
            <li><p>swap rows</p></li>
            <li><p>multiply a row by a non-zero scalar</p></li>
            <li><p>add a multiple of one row to another</p></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>We can represent each operation by a matrix multiplication with an elementary matrix.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <exercise>
      <title>Identifying Elementary Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose:
          <me>E \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
          By inspection, what is <m>E</m>? How does it compare to <m>I_3</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-elementary-inverse-connection">
    <title>Connection to the Inversion Algorithm</title>
    <p>
      Returning to understanding why our algorithm works, we apply a sequence of row operations to <m>A</m> to obtain <m>I_n</m>:
      <me>(E_k \dots E_3 E_2 E_1)A = I_n</me>
      Thus, the product <m>E_k \dots E_3 E_2 E_1</m> is the inverse matrix we seek.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-row-equivalence-invertibility">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Matrix <m>A</m> is invertible if and only if it is row equivalent to the identity. 
        </p>
        <p>
          In this case, any sequence of elementary row operations that transforms <m>A</m> into <m>I</m>, applied to <m>I</m>, generates <m>A^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-practical-inverse">
    <title>Using The Inverse to Solve a Linear System</title>
    <p>
      While we could use <m>A^{-1}</m> to solve a linear system <m>A\vec{x} = \vec{b}</m> by calculating <m>\vec{x} = A^{-1}\vec{b}</m>, it is seldom used in practice.
    </p>

    <note>
      <p>
        As our textbook points out, <m>A^{-1}</m> is rarely used because computing it:
        <ul>
          <li><p>can take a very long time</p></li>
          <li><p>is prone to numerical error</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        A recurring theme of this course: just because we <alert>can</alert> do something a certain way, does not mean that we <alert>should</alert>.
      </p>
    </note>
  </subsection>

  <summary>
    <p>We explored the following concepts in this section:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>elementary matrices and their relationship to row operations</p></li>
      <li><p>properties of the matrix inverse</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Elementary matrices are used a few times throughout this course to describe the processes behind algorithms.</p>
  </summary>
</section>